❓ WHY QUEUE
Queue stores:

Flip Ending Indices

Example:

Flip started at i = 3
k = 4

Effect rahega:

3,4,5,6

Queue me store:

6

Jab i = 6 aayega,
flip expire ho jayegi.

Thus queue batati hai:
kitni flips abhi active hain.

⏱️ COMPLEXITY
Time  : O(N)

Reason:
- Har flip ek baar queue me jaati hai.
- Har flip ek baar remove hoti hai.

Space : O(N)
(Worst Case)

🎯 INTERVIEW POINT
- Most important observation:

  Queue size % 2

  Even → original bit
  Odd  → flipped bit

- Actual k elements flip nahi kar rahe.
- Sirf active flip ranges track kar rahe hain.

- Greedy Decision:

  Agar current effective bit 0 hai,
  toh isi index se flip start karna mandatory hai.

  Future me koi flip is index ko affect nahi kar sakti.

- This is the classic:
  "Sliding Window + Lazy Flipping + Queue"
  optimization.

#Code:

import java.util.*;

public class Solution {
      public int minKBitFlips(int[] nums, int k) {
        //You can code here

        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        int n = nums.length;
        int count = 0;

        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
          if(q.size() % 2 != 0){
            //if odd then flip the current bit
            nums[i] = nums[i] ^ 1;
          }

          if(nums[i] == 0){
            if(i + k > n){
              return -1;
            }
            count++;
            q.offer(i+k-1);
          }

          if(!q.isEmpty() && q.peek() == i){
            q.poll();
          }
        }

        return count;
    }
}
